---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-israel', text: 'Leaving Israeli Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'kupat-holim', text: 'Kupat Holim Abroad', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'returning-to-israel', text: 'Returning to Israel', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Best US Coverage Insurance', href: '/best/us-coverage-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Europe Insurance', href: '/best/europe-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Premium Insurance', href: '/best/premium-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'hebrewSupport', header: 'Hebrew Support' },
  { key: 'usNetwork', header: 'US Network' },
  { key: 'israelCoverage', header: 'Israel Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', hebrewSupport: 'Limited', usNetwork: 'Strong', israelCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$200/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', hebrewSupport: 'Limited', usNetwork: 'Excellent', israelCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$220/mo' },
  { provider: 'Harel Insurance', hebrewSupport: 'Full (Hebrew)', usNetwork: 'Good', israelCoverage: 'Included', price: '$180/mo' },
  { provider: 'Clal Insurance', hebrewSupport: 'Full (Hebrew)', usNetwork: 'Good', israelCoverage: 'Included', price: '$175/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', hebrewSupport: 'Limited', usNetwork: 'Good', israelCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$190/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Israeli Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Israeli expats. Find coverage for the US, Germany, UK, and other destinations with options for Hebrew support."
  headline="Best Insurance for Israeli Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Israel's excellent healthcare doesn't follow you abroad. Here's how to stay protected while understanding your Kupat Holim rights and return options."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/israeli-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Israeli expats are concentrated in the US, Germany, UK, and Canada. Your insurance needs depend on your destination and how you want to maintain your connection to Israeli healthcare. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Israeli expats. Strong US networks (important for the large community there), comprehensive global coverage, reliable service.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent worldwide networks. Top-tier coverage and service.</li>
    <li><strong>Harel Insurance:</strong> Major Israeli insurer with international products. Full Hebrew service, includes Israel coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Clal Insurance:</strong> Another strong Israeli option. Hebrew service, Israel coverage included, competitive pricing.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good European coverage for Israeli expats in Germany and the UK.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Maintain Kupat Holim?"
    description="Israeli citizens can maintain their Kupat Holim membership while abroad. This protects your healthcare rights when you return and may provide limited coverage during visits. Consider this alongside international insurance."
    buttonText="Compare Insurance Options"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-israel">Leaving Israeli Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Israel has universal healthcare through the National Health Insurance Law. Every resident is a member of one of four Kupot Holim (health funds). Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>Residence Status</h3>
  <p>
    Your healthcare rights are tied to Israeli residence. When you report your departure to Bituach Leumi (National Insurance Institute), your status changes. After a certain period abroad, you may be considered a "resident abroad" (toshav chutz).
  </p>

  <h3>Continuing Kupat Holim Membership</h3>
  <p>
    Israeli citizens can continue paying Kupat Holim premiums while abroad. This maintains your membership and healthcare rights for when you return. However, this does NOT provide international coverage—you still need separate insurance abroad.
  </p>

  <h3>Bituach Leumi</h3>
  <p>
    Bituach Leumi (National Insurance) affects more than healthcare—it includes pension, disability, and other benefits. Report your departure to understand how your status and obligations change.
  </p>

  <h2 id="kupat-holim">Kupat Holim Abroad</h2>
  <p>
    Understanding your Kupat Holim options while abroad:
  </p>

  <h3>Maintaining Membership</h3>
  <p>
    You can maintain active Kupat Holim membership by continuing to pay premiums (either directly or through Bituach Leumi if applicable). Benefits include:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Healthcare access during visits to Israel</li>
    <li>No waiting periods when you return permanently</li>
    <li>Continued access to supplementary insurance (Shaban) benefits</li>
    <li>Peace of mind about return rights</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>What Kupat Holim Doesn't Provide</h3>
  <p>
    Kupat Holim membership does NOT cover:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Healthcare abroad (except very limited emergency assistance)</li>
    <li>International hospital bills</li>
    <li>Routine care outside Israel</li>
    <li>Evacuation or repatriation</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Supplementary Insurance (Shaban)</h3>
  <p>
    Many Israelis have Shaban (supplementary insurance) through their Kupat Holim. This may include limited international coverage—typically 30-90 days of emergency treatment. Review your specific policy, but don't rely on Shaban for long-term international coverage.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Tax Implications</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Israel has complex tax rules for citizens abroad. Maintaining certain ties (including ongoing Kupat Holim payments) may affect your tax residency status. Consult an Israeli tax advisor before leaving.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive international coverage ideal for Israeli expats, particularly those in the US where many Israelis relocate. Strong networks, three coverage tiers with limits up to unlimited, and efficient claims processing.
  </p>

  <p>
    Hebrew support is limited, but English service is excellent 24/7. Most Israelis are comfortable with English. Israel coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Israeli expats who want reliable global coverage, especially in the US.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium international coverage with excellent networks worldwide. Service quality matches Israeli healthcare expectations. Comprehensive benefits including mental health and maternity.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pricing is higher but reflects premium positioning. Good for professionals who can afford top-tier coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Israeli expats who want the best coverage available.
  </p>

  <h3>Harel Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Harel is one of Israel's largest insurance companies, offering international health products for Israelis abroad. Full Hebrew service, familiar processes, and Israel coverage included automatically.
  </p>

  <p>
    International networks are adequate, strongest in Europe and North America. Good option for those preferring an Israeli provider.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Israeli expats who want Hebrew service and seamless Israel coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Clal Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Clal offers similar international coverage to Harel. Full Hebrew service, Israel coverage included, competitive pricing. Another strong Israeli option for expats who prefer dealing with a familiar company.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Israeli expats seeking good value from a familiar Israeli brand.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Israeli and International Options"
    description="Israeli insurers offer Hebrew service and included Israel coverage. International insurers often have stronger global networks. Compare based on your needs."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="returning-to-israel">Returning to Israel</h2>
  <p>
    Returning to Israeli healthcare depends on how you've maintained your status:
  </p>

  <h3>If You Maintained Kupat Holim</h3>
  <p>
    Return is seamless. Your healthcare rights are intact, and you can immediately access Kupat Holim services. Update your address and health fund with your return.
  </p>

  <h3>If You Didn't Maintain Membership</h3>
  <p>
    You may face waiting periods before full healthcare access. The rules vary based on how long you were abroad and your circumstances. Contact Bituach Leumi before returning to understand your specific situation.
  </p>

  <h3>Re-registering</h3>
  <p>
    Report your return to Misrad HaPnim (Interior Ministry) and Bituach Leumi. Update your Kupat Holim registration with your Israeli address.
  </p>

  <h3>Transition Period</h3>
  <p>
    Keep your international insurance active until Israeli coverage is confirmed. If there are waiting periods, international insurance bridges the gap.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Does my Kupat Holim cover me abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Very minimally. Basic Kupat Holim provides almost no international coverage. Shaban may provide limited emergency coverage, but you need proper international insurance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Should I maintain Kupat Holim payments?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">If you might return to Israel, maintaining membership protects your rights and avoids waiting periods. The cost is relatively low for peace of mind.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about coverage during Israel visits?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">If you've maintained Kupat Holim, you're covered during visits. Otherwise, your international insurance should include Israel as a coverage region.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is Harel or Cigna better?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Harel offers Hebrew service and includes Israel. Cigna has stronger US networks. Choose based on your destination and language preference.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Are there Hebrew-speaking doctors abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">In cities with Israeli communities (New York, Los Angeles, Berlin), you can find Hebrew-speaking doctors. Your insurer can help locate providers.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about Bituach Leumi pension?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Pension rights depend on your contributions and years in Israel. Contact Bituach Leumi to understand how time abroad affects your entitlements.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Israeli expats need comprehensive international insurance—Kupat Holim doesn't provide meaningful coverage abroad. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for reliable coverage, especially for the US. <strong>Bupa Global</strong> offers premium coverage for those who want the best.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Harel</strong> and <strong>Clal</strong> are ideal for those wanting Hebrew service and included Israel coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    Consider maintaining Kupat Holim membership alongside international insurance—it protects your return rights and costs relatively little. And consult with Bituach Leumi and a tax advisor before leaving to understand all implications.
  </p>

</PageShell>
